  <oversight_info>
    <has_dmc>No</has_dmc>
  </oversight_info>
  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Computer Aided Surgery in total knee arthroplasty improves knee stability and functional
      outcomes more than conventional total knee arthroplasty.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
  <detailed_description>
    <textblock>
      The success of total knee arthroplasty depends on restoration of limb alignment, precise
      implant positioning and optimal gap balancing. The advent of computer aided surgery (CAS) has
      improved limb alignment and implant positioning. The objective of this study was to evaluate
      the functional outcome of computer aided soft tissue gap balancing in total knee
      arthroplasty.
    </textblock>
  </detailed_description>
